<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN MINISTER SENDS CONDOLENCE TO LATE TAIWAN ATHLETE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles,  Jan.  30 (CNA) 01/30/07  18:58:16 (By Ruth Wang)
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Affairs James Huang praised the great
achievements of Yang Chuan-Kwang, a Taiwan athlete who died in
his California home Sunday, in a telegram of condolence, a Taipei
official post here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wei Wu-lien, director-general of the Taipei Economic and Cultural
Office (TECO) in Los Angeles, said he drove to Yang's residence
at Thousand Oaks City in Ventura County earlier the day, to hand
the condolence telegram to Yang's wife, Daisy Chou, and the
couple's sons Cedric Yang, and C.K. Yang Jr.
</P>
<P>
According to Wei, the office will help handle funeral affairs
with Yang's family.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who died at the age of 73 from brain hemorrhage, was known
for wining Taiwan's first Olympic medal, a silver in decathlon,
in Rome 1960.
</P>
<P>
Yang's funeral ceremony will be held at 11 a.m. Feb. 3 at Ted
Mayr Funeral Home and Crematory in Ventura County, California.
The TECO will place the national flag of the Republic of China on
Yang's coffin according to governmental regulations.
</P>
